  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>CHAPTER 4: BANISHMENT</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><p>-----</p>
<font size="+3">Chapter 4: Banishment</font>
<p>-----</p>

<p>	Getting out of Neriak had been surprisingly easy.  First the necromancer had used her dark magics to heal Ravell's wounds.  Ravell then had exited the chamber used to imprison him through a passageway hiding behind an illusionary wall.  Just outside of that chamber was a room filled with all of his weapons and armor, and Ravell equipped himself again.  After that, he followed the passageway until he found himself just outside the Neriak gates, out of view of the two guards on duty.  Now Ravell sat at the edge of the pirahna-filled river of Nektulos forest, staring at the wooden bridge in the distance.  A heavy rain blanketed the forest, as it often did.  Ravell watched the droplets landing in the river absently, remembering the last time he set foot in this forest.</p>
<p>	"Perhaps I should just jump in and let the pirahnas get me." Ravell whispered to himself.  "T'would be a better fate than being a slave for the rest of my life."  Ravell sighed, now shifting his view to the foggy treetops of the dark forest.  "I've never worshipped Innoruuk, but I cannot imagine leaving this place behind.  The wretched world of the lightskins is now my world, I cannot be a part of Innoruuk's glorious forest and town anymore.  No...perhaps in time I will redeem myself.  Aye, first I shall free myself of this collar, then I shall kill my dark master.  Her dying breath will tell me how to fall back into favor with the Indigo Brotherhood."</p>
<p>	Ravell smiled and looked back to the waters of the river.  "For now I just have to get to befallen."  Without another word the drow jumped in and swam as fast as he could manage.  Only a couple Pirahnas attacked, and they made only small cuts and bites on Ravell.  He again found himself lucky, as he arrived at the other river bank without being seriously wounded.  Sitting a moment to bandage his fresh cuts, Ravell began trying to think of a way to rid himself of his collar.</p>
<p>-----</p>

<p>	Garit leaned on the railing of the boat, staring off at the distant clouds.  Behind him, his young sister sat by a mast holding the half-elf child.  "How does he fare?  I have seen young ones get sick traveling in a boat."</p>
<p>	"He is certainly cute, isn't he?  Don't worry, he seems to be having less trouble than I am on this rickety thing." The young high elf replied.</p>
<p>	Garit turned to look at the pair. "Lenia, why did you leave home behind?"</p>
<p>	The beautiful young elf looked hurt. "Do you not want me with you?"</p>
<p>	"Of course I do.  I left because I could no longer stay quiet in the face of our father's pride.  He is not an evil elf, but I fear his age has left him jaded." Garit answered.</p>
<p>	"If you must know, I left for many of the same reasons you did brother.  I believe everyone should have a fair chance to prove their character, regardless of race.  Even those hideous trolls and evil dark elves deserve a chance.  I also have always wanted to see the world." Lene bundled up the baby tighter as the sea breeze picked up.</p>
<p>	Garit walked up and looked at the child.  "Sister, you must be careful with those beliefs.  Certainly they are beautiful ideals, but you must understand.  Dark elves, trolls, ogres, these creatures come from societies where they are rewarded for being merciless, ruthless, and evil.  I don't deny the fact that they may be born with a good heart, but their society corrupts them as they grow.  I don't want to crush your ideals, sister, but I feel you should be cautious.  Do not take it too hard if you are unable to find goodness in the evil races."</p>
<p>	Lenia nodded.  "I plan to be cautious, of course.  But I will take the same amount of caution with every person, and give them my friendship when we first meet.  If they do not return it, or reject it completely lies in their own selves, and perhaps that shall be a true test of character."</p>
<p>	"Well spoken, sister.  I am very glad to see that father has not corrupted your beautiful spirit.  Enough talk of this for now, have you thought of a name for the child?" Garit crouched down and smiled.</p>
<p>	"Actually," Lenia began, examining the corners of the child's blanket for something. "Ahh here it is.  They already named it, or so I think.  It's right here, embroidered onto the blanket.  They named him Daisho."</p>
<p>	"Not a name I'd have chosen." Garit frowned.  "Ah well, 'tis just fine for the little one."</p>
<p>	Lenia looked over her shoulder towards the front of the boat. "Look brother.  Is that Freeport?"</p>
<p>	"Aye, sis.  Let's get through here quickly, I dislike this town." Garit stood to observe the nearing docks.</p>
<p>-----</p>

<p>	Ravell stood awestruck at the entrance to Nektulos Forest.  He gazed upward, jaw slightly ajar.  The young drow fighter had never seen the sky, or clouds before.  "How beautiful," He thought.  Looking up at the endless blue sky with its clouds drifting overhead, Ravell began to question his dark lord for the first time.  For the first time in his short life, the drow felt insignificant.  This was strangely comforting to Ravell.  While looking at the gorgeous sky overhead, Ravell was allowed a brief moment of clarity where he was able to see himself and his beliefs clearly.  Why should he bring hatred to a world capable of this beauty?  Why would he ever want to change this into something like the oppressive forest he had just left behind?</p>
<p>	"What are you gaping at, warrior?  First time you've been outside Nektulos?" A familiar female voice interrupted Ravell's thought process.</p>
<p>	"Lilith!  It is good to see you alive and well." Ravell turned to see the black-armored shadowknight standing behind him with a rogue next to her wearing blackened chainmail.</p>
<p>	"I heard about you being banished, and I don't agree with it.  I wanted you to know I pulled as many strings as possible, but it wasn't enough.  I'm sorry." Lilith's sincerety sounded strange to Ravell. He had never heard her talk about anything except killing.</p>
<p>	"No worries, my friend.  I will return to Neriak, and we will fight alongside each other again." Ravell vowed.</p>
<p>	The rogue with Lilith moved forward and grabbed her by the arm.  "We must be going.  You cannot be seen with an outcast."  He put an extra emphasis on the word 'outcast'.</p>
<p>	Lilith sighed.  "Alright, then.  Ravell I wish you luck."</p>
<p>	Saluting, the shadowknight turned and walked off and quickly vanished into the hills with her rogue partner.  Ravell watched her go and again began to question what had just happened.  Perhaps being an outcast wasn't such a bad thing.  Despite her kind words, Ravell suddenly  felt sorry for Lilith.  She was nothing but a tool of a god who did not care for his people.</p>
<p>	"What am I thinking?!" Ravell suddenly snapped at himself.  "Idiot! You will go to Befallen, you will slay the shadowknight, you will return and slay your enslaver, and then you will redeem yourself somehow and return to Neriak! You will not think such blasphemous thoughts ever again!"</p>
<p>	Ravell forced the thoughts out of his head.  This was how the other gods corrupted the other races.  This was what made them weak.  Yes, the weaker gods tricked their foolish followers with beauty and empty gifts.  After all, was not the most beautiful snake also the most poisonous?  Did the greatest gift ever given not come with the heaviest hidden price?  A trap made by the weaker gods to fool others into following them, and he had nearly fallen into it.  Feeling more like his old self, Ravell began to walk towards Befallen.</p>
<p>-----</p>

<p>	Lenia and Garit walked along the winding paths of the commonlands, headed west.  They had rushed through Freeport so quickly Lenia had barely had a chance to take in all the sights.  She somehow got the feeling that all was not as it should be in that town, as Garit walked just a bit faster than usual and kept his hand on his sword hilt.  Still, the young elf did not worry.  She was with her experienced brother, and she was determined to see what she could of the world.  She took a moment to enjoy the scenery, a mixture of small hills with a desert forming at the side.  A few small inns and huts lined the roadway, and though they didn't stop at any Lenia could guess at the lack of quality held within.  </p>
<p>	"Garit," She began without slowing in her tracks. "Where are we going?  I had thought we would stop at Freeport at least for the night."</p>
<p>	"Tonight we will bed down in Rivervale, sister, and within the next week we shall reach the city of Qeynos.  It is a humble place enough to serve as a home for the child, and perhaps the temple of Rodcet Nife will be able to tell me something of what happened to our brother." Garit replied out of the corner of his mouth.</p>
<p>	"Rivervale! But to get there we must travel through Kithicor." Lenia protested.</p>
<p>	Garit smiled slightly.  "Fear not, sister.  Kithicor is safe enough in the daytime, and we have plenty of time to reach Rivervale.  The day after that we shall visit High Keep, within Highpass.  If time allows we will continue onward into the Western Karanas and stay at a small inn out there.  Past that it will be nothing but farmland and plains for days, so we should make decent time."</p>
<p>	Lenia tried to imagine the trip, but did not know of half of the places her brother spoke of.  She gave up quickly and again tried to take in the scenery when she saw something.  "Brother!  Do you see that?"</p>
<p>	Garit stopped and looked to where his sister was pointing.  "Yes, Lenia.  It is merely a drow heading towards the undead ruins of Befallen.  Let's keep moving."</p>
<p>	"But brother, " Lenia looked hopefully at her brother.  "You promised me you would show me the world.  I wish to see this undead place, and to meet this drow who would enter alone."</p>
<p>	"Lenia, we must hurry! If we do not make it to Rivervale before nightfall we will have to stay in an inn out here.  If the dark elf plans to enter the ruins alone then he is likely an inhabitant.  There are many necromancers and shadowknights who call that place home.  It is not a pleasant place, and I would rather not take the child in." Garit turned and crossed his arms.</p>
<p>	Mimicking her brother's stance, Lenia argued.  "What's one more night? Rivervale can wait.  Besides, I would like to meet a drow elf and see if he lives up to the stories our parents told us as children.  I'm sure that you can handle any trouble I might get us into.  I will keep the child safe if you must fight."</p>
<p>	Garit frowned, trying to judge the time by looking at the sky.  "You will someday get into too much trouble with that attitude, sister."</p>
<p>	Lenia smiled, knowing she almost had her brother convinced.  One more word would win the arguement for her.  "Please?"  She asked in her sweetest possible voice.</p>
<p>	Garit growled in frustration.  "All right!  But don't be surprised if this drow does live up to the stories, they have a tendency to do that."</p>
<p>	Lenia would have jumped happily in the air if she didn't have the baby bundled to her back.</p>
<p>-----</p>
 </font></td>
	</tr>
